I’ve had many people ask what my advice would be heading into 2023. So here it is! 

⚡️ Get in touch with your body.
Listen to your body. Find food that’ll nourish you. If you are bloating or crashing after food, that’s NOT healthy. Your body is rejecting it. If you are crashing midday, and you chase a caffeine high.. QUIT. You need to EAT. You don’t need a cup of coffee. Listen to your body! 

⚡️ WALK. So many of you just sit.. ALL DAY. if you work from home. Change your desk. Get a walking pad. Take breaks and move. Get your steps in. You’ll burn more calories, your body will feel better, and you’ll thank me later. Being sedentary will be the death for some.

⚡️ LIFT HEAVY. Lifting heavy will not make you bulky. It’ll help you lose fat, build muscle, and transform you mentally. I express all the time to lift heavy. If you want to make progress, you must lift. Cardio will only get you so far. 

⚡️ Find consistency. Quit going hard for 12 weeks and then falling off for 6. Find balance. Find a program you’ll love. Find food that you will love and that’s beneficial for you. Most of the time, if you are feeding your body properly, you eventually won’t crave junk. Create a schedule. Set boundaries for yourself. Go to bed at a certain time, and hold yourself accountable. 

⚡️ Last but not least, quit the excuses. Like the wall says, shut up and train. You have more control than you think. You are the holder of your life. If you want it, you’ll do it. If you don’t, then there’s your answer. Take control. Work hard. Tuck your head low. And take care of yourself. Seek guidance. Ask for help. And start showing up for you! 

If you need help. Have questions. Want to talk. I’m always here! Time to put 2022 behind and focus on what’s to come 💪🏼

Six Tips for Barbell Squats 💪🏼💥

📍 Find the best positioning for your body 
 
How is your mobility? If you tend to have long femurs, and lack of mobility, low bar squatting will be your best friend. Setting the bar on your traps and allowing your body to lean forward. 

📍  Use proper squat shoes, or no shoes
In this video I am wearing squat shoes, but I personally prefer to be barefoot. 

📍 Push through your entire foot 
All your power comes from your feet. Make sure all points of your foot are pressed evenly into the ground on the way up, and way down. 

📍 Brace your core 

Pull your belly button into your spine and fill your belly up with air, with every rep. 

📍 Practice without weight first 

Practice makes perfect. Make sure you are able to perform a squat without weight first. Can’t make depth? Something hurts? You need to warm up more and reevaluate before putting weight on. 

📍 Perform all reps the same way

95 lbs or 275lbs all reps must be the same. Imagine every rep is your 1RM. Be steady, careful, and focus.

FOUR Reasons Why You Aren’t Hitting Your Fitness Goals ❗️

📍You don’t set boundaries for yourself. 
You might think.. setting boundaries? Yeah.. like setting a bed time/wake up time? Taking one hour out of your day to schedule in some kind of activity. Letting people know what you are doing so they can support you. Not feeling guilty when you take “me” time. Anything. Scheduling, setting boundaries with yourself, will help you be successful. Sometimes even your own self can sabotage yourself. 

📍 Setting unrealistic goals 
Let’s be real.. you won’t be the weight you were in high school. You won’t look the same after kids. Hormones change. Lives change. Puberty etc. setting goals that are unrealistic will lead you to fail. Getting to a certain weight and having a number stick in your head, will drive you nuts. Trying to workout 7 days a week? Not healthy. Only eating chicken, veggies and rice? Sounds like a disaster. 
Start small.. focus on nailing your workouts first. Focus on getting 10,000 steps a day. Then slowly change your food. Then everything else will fall into place. 

📍 Binge eating

Sigh.. I’ve been there. It’s tough. You restrict yourself so much, that you go off the deep end. You have a “cheat meal” or “cheat day” mentality. Cheat meals/ days can ruin your entire progress for the week. I’m not saying to not indulge.. I’m saying, do it in moderation. Make smarter choices. Cut out the drink, don’t go for the appetizer, maybe share the meal? Sub out things. Put sauces on the side. There are so many things you can do, so you can enjoy going out. Don’t restrict yourself.. just make sure you are aware of your choices. 

📍Not taking responsibility for your own choices. 
You have kids, life, animals, job, etc… but guess what, we all do? The reality is.. you have a choice. You choose to make time to workout. You choose the food you put into your mouth.. no one is force feeding you. You choose not to go to bed on time. Everything is a choice. Now I get it, life does happen.. but end of the day, you can’t always blame others for why you can’t do something. You can, you just have to adjust.

“The one who fails and gets up is stronger than the one who never tried.”

SIX Reasons Why You Should Strength Train❗️

✅ Makes you stronger 
We all like to feel powerful don’t we? Strength training not only makes you stronger physically, but emotionally and mentally. It is okay to do the hard things! 

✅Burns calories more efficiently 
In order to burn calories throughout the day, you must build muscle. The more you strength train, the more muscle you’ll put on, the more calories you’ll burn throughout the day. Yeah, you’ll burn calories doing cardio, but only for that time ;) 

✅ Makes your bones stronger 
Simple as that. We need our bones to be strong to support ourselves! 

✅ Builds your confidence 
There’s nothing better than crushing a goal/PR. Strength training is about seeing what YOU are capable of. 

✅ Build your body the way you want it 
I’m sorry but you won’t get the booty or back that you want but doing the stair master or running. Good form, heavy but manageable weight, will help you develop the body of your dreams. 

✅ Better quality of life 
I personally train for health all the way around. My mental release. To make me feel like a bad ass. To strengthen my body all the way through. I can tell the days I do lift vs I don’t. It might drag during or before, but once you’re done.. you are like a whole new person! 

When I tell you to lift heavier in class.. trust me. You’ll thank me later 🫶🏼

Fat loss vs weight loss are TWO different things. 

Weight loss and water weight are tricky things. So many factors affect this.

🔹activity 
🔹sodium

🔹stress, etc. 

Any of those factors could make your weight go up, and go down.

Are you eating enough? 

Are you enjoying what you’re eating? 

Are you still hungry?

You are more likely to “fall off the wagon” if you despise what you are eating. We need to create a healthy relationship with food between your mind and body. 

And the last one, are you still hungry? 
Most times if you are still hungry after you ate, it’s your body’s way of telling you it needs more food, or, you didn’t have a complete meal. Either way, revaluate what you just ate.. if you need more, it’s okay.

I’m about to get real with everyone. I think a lot of people need the friendly reminder that the scale… is not your friend. In fact, it’s your enemy. If you are chasing a number.. you’ll never be happy. You’ll never be satisfied. You will always want more. I had to learn that the hard way, and that’s okay :)

For those of you who haven’t seen my journey, my top weight was 400lbs at 18 years old. I was in a very dark place at that time, and felt completely lost and helpless. 

Fast forward and swipe to the next photo.. with the help of a few coaches, who unfortunately were NOT the best. It was crash diet after diet. Extremely low calories, and much more. But hey, I got to 170 lbs.. that’s all I cared about. I didn’t care about anything else. I just wanted to be small. I didn’t want to be the “big girl” anymore. And even at 170 lbs I was still miserable. I still thought of myself as fat. 

Body dysmorphia  will do that to you. 

I was obsessive. Unhealthy. You name it. 

Swipe to the next, my body started rejecting me. My hormones were shutting down. I have ruined my metabolism. I put on 30 lbs but felt better. I was eating more, still working out, competing at a high level in powerlifting, but still… thought of myself as fat. 

And now we swipe the last. My current physique. The body that has been through so much. A tarnished metabolism. Stretch marks, extra skin.

I’ve struggled. I’ve overcame my eating disorders. I have found my balance. And now after 3 years of gaining weight, I am at the point of being able to lose weight in a healthy way. Not a destructive way.  I have taken the last year plus to get in tune with my body vs obsess over the scale. And I’m so thankful I did. I have never felt better. 

A lot of the learning came with time. Trial and error. Developing my own education. 

And I wouldn’t change it for the world. 

Quit chasing the unattainable. Quit being drastic. Obsessive. Your journey is more than just that. 

❤️ Shania

Unfortunately, the fitness industry is not immune to scams and frauds. From bogus supplements to fake workout programs, there are people out there who will try to take advantage of your desire to get fit and healthy.

So, how can you spot a fitness scam? Here are some red flags to watch out for:

🚩 Promises of quick and easy results: There are no shortcuts to getting fit and healthy. If a product or program claims that you can achieve your goals with minimal effort or in a short amount of time, it’s probably too good to be true.

🚩 Exaggerated claims: Be wary of products that make unrealistic or exaggerated claims. For example, a supplement that promises to “burn fat while you sleep” is unlikely to deliver on its promise.

Remember, getting fit and healthy is a journey that takes time and effort. Don’t fall for fitness scams that promise quick and easy results. Instead, focus on making sustainable lifestyle changes that will help you achieve your goals in the long run. 💪

Everybody has a fitness journey. 

I’ve recently talked a lot about how Fitness isn’t about losing weight or necessarily transforming your body. A fitness journey  is about healing certain internal issues. It is about making sure you are healthy in all aspects. Spiritual, mental, emotional. Etc. 

I haven’t really opened up about my own journey in the last year. Every year it changes. Sometimes for the better, and sometimes for the worst and it’s all about how you handle it. 

I have dealt with unexplained weight gain. Yes I eat well, exercise etc. I even quit drinking. And all 90% of the doctors have said is to eat better to exercise more. 

I then get diagnosed with lymes disease, mold, and much more. My arthritis has been at an all time high, and I broke my ankle. 

On top of all this, my mental health was so trash, and I was on such toxic medication. If I were to get pregnant it would automatically give me an abortion, and if I forgot to take it my body would completely shut down. I dealt with dark thoughts for more than half the year. It got scary for a moment, but I never showed that side to anyone. I sought out  help. Lots of therapy I might add. And healed, and now I’m better. 

As I have been extremely uncomfortable in my own body, I had to take a step back and realize that I need to heal internally before even tackling the external portion. 

I need to learn how to sleep more than 5 hours. I need to learn how to slow down. I need to learn to get over the years of trauma I’ve endured. Learn to love exercise again. How to take care of myself, and how to let others take care of me. That way I can become the healthiest version of myself. 

The thing is, if I’m not happy and healed on the inside, it won’t matter how I look on the outside. I’ll still tear myself down. 

My journey this year has been unlike anything else. It’s been soul searching. Searching for who “Shania” is. Because let’s face it? I had no clue. And it ate at me. It tore me down. It’s been healing. It’s been A LOT. 

If you are struggling to find your way in your own fitness journey, remember - you have to heal internal, before you can tackle the external.
